Motivation

Many of the world’s largest and fastest-growing cities–from Karachi (pop. 14 million; 34.6% increase from 2000-2010) to Delhi (22m; 39.4%), Dhaka (15m, 45.2%), Jakarta (10m; 14.8%), Bangkok (8m, 29.1%), Lagos (11m; 48.2%) and Kinshasa (9m, 55.4%)–are located in South Asia and Sub-Saharan Africa with tropical to sub-tropical climates unlike those of most OECD member cities in the global North. As the tropics/sub-tropics become increasingly urban, inudstrial and affluent, it is important to consider how energy demand–particularly for thermal comfort–will evolve differently in these places than it has historically across the OECD.

To illustrate the potential for vast differences in energy demand for thermal comfort between cities in the global North and cities in the Tropics/Sub-Tropics, consider Delhi, India. Delhi–with its massive population and very hot climate–is an outlier compared to OECD member cities but typical of South Asia: Peak summer temperatures routinely exceed 40 deg C. (104 F.), and intense heatwaves can approach 50 deg C. (122 F.). Given the huge temperature differential between outdoor (say 104 F.) and desired indoor air temperature (say 72 F), and the thermodynamic fact that energy for cooling scales linearly with the temperature differential, cooling a room in Delhi requires twice as much energy as cooling a room in New York where the summer outdoor-indoor temperature differential is typically half that.

In addition to higher temperatures, the summer season is also much longer: in the past year, Delhi had over six times as many cooling-degree days as New York City (again assuming a desired indoor air temperature of 72 deg F). Compounded by leaky building envelopes in developing world cities (designed for natural ventilation, not air conditiong), intense heat-island effects (typically less green space), and massive population growth, peak electricity demand in cities thourought the developing world could one day surpass that of their neighbors to the north–not only in aggregate terms because of their population, but also per-capita due to climate, building design and thermodynamics.

Figure 1 provides a map of urbanization rates for cities worldwide with a population greater than 750,000 (UN 2011). Urbanization rates are clearly highest in South Asia and Sub-Saharan Africa. Figure 2 shows the distribution of population growth rates for the same set of cities, grouped by latitude (global North, Tropics and Subtropics). The expected value (e.g. central tendancy) of urbanization rates in the Tropics and Sub-Tropics is clearly distinct from that of the North.

Implications of Global Energy Service Provision Parity

If we consider the trajectory of economic development in emerging cities as reaching eventual parity with OECD cities, then we must think in terms of energy service provision, not just BTU or KWh. Households and businesses do not demand energy per-se, but energy services such as thermal comfort (air conditiong and heating), food storage (refrigeration), food preperation (oven, stove, microwave, pressure cooker, etc..) productivity (computers), communication (mobile phones), and entertainment (TV). Therefore, mid- to long-range forecasts of energy demand must consider how demand for energy services will evolve over time.

Economists have studied demand for energy services from several angles. The World Bank analyzed monthly expenditures for 600 households in India, split between urban and rural adoption rates of household applicances, and thus (indirectly) disaggregated demand for energy services…

The income elasticity of thermal comfort seeking behavior in emerging economies will determine global peak electricity demand in the coming decades. This will have huge implications on regional grid planning, capacity expansion, technology deployment, prices, incentive structures and overall system reliability. More broadly, it will have implications on the global transition to renewable energy given the limitations of meeting such large and ‘peaky’ demand with non-dispatchable resources such as wind and solar.

Applications

Mid- to long-range global energy demand forecasts are typically reported as annual totals and provide little insight to the temporal distribution throughout the year. To address this shortcoming, we focus on the diurnal and seasonal distribution of energy demand and supply, which drive system cost but recieve relatively little attention in global energy outlooks. This requires more and better data than is typically available to researchers.

Drivers of Urban Energy Demand

Broadly speaking, economic activity (as measured by GDP) drives annual average energy use, climate drives seasonal variability, and human physiology and local weather drive diurnal variability. This study considers all three – GDP, climate and weather.

Climate Perspective in Energy Demand Forecasts

Daily and seasonal variability in urban electricity demand is caused, to a large degree, by the usage of cooling and heating devices, which is most significantly affected by meteorological factors. (Segal et al. ,1992; Later Thatcher, 2007)

Segal et al. (1992) evaluated, at regional level, the interrelationship between the summer peak energy consumption in Israel and pertinent meteorological parameters. This paper proposed a classic linear regression model between climate and electricity demand that is very often referred to in later literature. Crowley et al. (2003) analyzed the role of climate change-driven effects on electricity demand in both residential and commercial sectors, which are considered to be most sensitive to temperature changes. The study predicted using actual temperature data an average demand increase of 3.8% in Pennsylvania, New Jersey and Maryland. Later Thatcher (2007) built a demand predicting model base on Segal et al’s study, which uses only daily max/min temperature and relative humidity as input to estimate electricity demand. The author first took daily max/min temperature to estimate apparent temperature in 30-mins’ intervals using sine-exponential technique; then use the modified linear regression model between climate and demand to obtain the prediction of electricity demand. The model was also applied to estimate how Load Duration Curves (LDC) change as a result of a 1 degree increase in the average temperature in Australian state capital cities.

Econometric Perspective in Energy Demand Forecasts

Many different approaches dealing with this issue are found in literature, and can be categorized into macro-level approaches and micro-level approaches. Macroeconomic approach uses macro data at the country or sub-national/state level to estimate the income elasticity of electricity consumption. One example is Bose and Shukla’s (1999) research. On the other hand, microeconomic approach uses micro-level data that reflects individual and household behavior to analyze across different heterogeneous household sub-groups. Examples are Tiwari (2000), Pachauri (2004), The World Bank (2008).

Predictions for tropic and sub-tropical cities

As tropical and sub-tropical cities become increasingly urban, industrialized and affluent, Pachauri and Spreng (2004) found that urban households in India would change energy consumption patterns. They would consume more energy per capita and would move from less efficiency energy sources such as biomass and kerosene to more efficient energy sources such as electricity and LPG, therefore leading to an increase in peak electricity demand and consumption.

A seminal paper on the relation between climate, electricity demand and prediction model was made by Segal et al. (1992). The author studied the correlation between peak electricity load and meteorological parameters (temperature, humidity and wind speeds) and proposed a regression model modeling this relation. Subsequently, Thatcher (2007), based on Segal Et Al.’s model, derived an effective electricity demand model that uses time (data and specific time) and relative temperatures as inputs and that outputs fairly accurate forecasted demand at 30 minutes resolution. These 2 studies, however, provide detailed modeling for a particular mature utility and are therefore hard to generalize to other locations (i.e. developing world region).

In terms of electricity demand sensitivity to climate in the developing regions, 2 studies by the same author (Gupta, Indian Statistical Institute, Delhi, India) were reviewed. The first one (2012) adopted a semi-parametric coefficient model that allowed the temperature-electricity relation to vary over time for Delhi. Its main findings were that electricity demand is a U-shaped function of temperature and that the cooling demand per unit increase in temperature is increasing over time. The second study by the same author (2014) took into account 28 Indian states and did not constraint itself to only 1 city. From this study, Gupta found that the summer electricity demand sensitivity to temperature is higher in hotter climate Indian states and that similarly, winter electricity demand sensitivity to temperature is higher in colder Indian states. He hypothesized that, it was because in hotter climate states people used more energy units of cooling equipment, and similarly, in colder states people used more energy units of heating equipment. He also conjectured that the effect of both hotter and colder weather on electricity demand sensitivity would be more pronounced with higher incomes and GDP/Capita. This study takes Gupta’s 2014 paper (2014) a step further by doing a global survey, including international emerging and developed cities from the US, West Africa, South Asia and South East Asia, and mapping their sensitivity properties by socio-economic and geographic factors.

Data

In order to achieve the objective of our research, we looked for electricity demand data, weather data, GDP data, and population data for cities ranging all over the world, with more focus placed on largest and fastest growing cities in tropics and subtropics. We expect the number of cities that we have for demand, weather, GDP and population data corresponding to each other as many as possible.

Weather Data

The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) offers a variety of free meteorological and climatological information through the National Climatic Data Center. The data is available on the Online Climate Data Directory website, available via FTP, which we can download and efficiently process in R. We chose the weather stations closest to our cities of interest, and eliminated the invalid data (missing values, 999s and NAs) to get the climatic information for each city of interest in terms of temperature, wind speed, wind direction, dew point temperature, and atmospheric pressure. Key Concepts

Load Duration Curve (LDC)

A load duration curve illustrates the relationship between generating capacity requirements and capacity utilization. It shows the variation of a certain load in a decreasing order of magnitude such that the highest load is plotted in the left and the lowest in the right. The height of each slice is a measure of capacity; the width of each slice is a measure of the utilization rate or capacity factor; the product of the two is a measure of electrical energy.

CDD/HDD

Cooling degree days and heating degree days are measurements that reflect the amount of energy demand needed to cool or heat a building. The cooling/heating requirement at a specific location is considered to be proportional to its CDD/HDD.Cooling degree hours and heating degree hours can be defined similarly but at hourly level.

\[ {CDD} = max\left \{ T_{ave} - T_{b}, 0 \right \} {HDD} = max\left \{ T_{b} - T_{ave}, 0 \right \} \]

Temperature-Load Curve

In general, the relationship between temperature and electricity can be described by a U-shaped curve. This U-shaped curve is estimated in many literature using different approaches. The simplest one is to use a regression model that is quadratic in temperature.

[figure 1 omitted]

Temperature-Load Coefficient We have both weather and demand data for 40 cities spanning the north, tropics and subtropics areas. For each city, we did segmented or linear regression on the scaled demand and temperature to get the hourly and overall demand-temperature coefficients.

Threshold temperature The lowest point on the estimated U-shape temperature-electricity curve is the threshold temperature denoting 1) the temperature above which people start to use cooling appliances and below which start to use heating appliances; 2) and the base electricity load that is independent from demand for cooling or heating.

Methods

Two main analyses are performed in this study. The first one consists in deriving the peak electricity demand climate sensitivity (cooling coefficient) and threshold temperature for every city, and the second consists in mapping this sensitivity measure of cities to socio-economic factors.

For both cases, the flow chart of operations is very similar.

Because there is usually no economic and commercial activities in the weekends compared to weekdays, demand for electricity is expected to be lower on weekends. To avoide this noise in the analyses, corresponding observations are disregarded.

Starting with the temperature and load profile of a city, the temperature-load profile can be obtained by making correspond the load to the matching temperature. Plotting the load against the temperature, one obtains the temperature-load curve. Depending on the city, this profile can either be in the form of a “V” shape, or of a “cloud” shape.

The below leftward figure is a clear “V” shape temperature-load curve for New York City. The right side of the curve represents the cooling regime: as temperatures increase, demand for electricity increases because of cooling requirements. The cooling regime, and therefore the city’s sensitivity to high temperatures, is characterized by a positive coefficient called the cooling coefficient. The left side of the curve represents the heating regime; as temperatures decrease, demand for electricity increases because of heating requirements (although the main heating requirements are not power by electricity but natural gas, some heating appliances do use electricity). The city’s sensitivity to cold temperatures is characterized by a negative coefficient called the heating coefficient, which tend to be lower in absolute terms compared to cooling coefficient.

In constrast, the below rightward figure is a clear “cloud” shape temperature-load curve for Accra. This shape indicates that the city is only in the cooling regime as temperatures are always high.

The above correleations being made for observations at all hours of the day, subsetting them by daily peak load would give the “maximum” temperature-load relation for every city.

The above procedure was applied for absolute load values.

To ensure comparability between cities of different sizes (i.e. putting the load on the same scale), the same procedure is repeated for the scaled load for every city at every hour. Isolating the data by city and hour of day, scaling the load consists in subtracting the average of load to the observed load and dividing by the standard deviation, as per the following formula:

\[ \textrm{Scaled load} = \frac{\textrm{Observed load - Average of observed loads}}{\textrm{Standard Deviation of observed loads}} \]

The scaled coefficients are therefore obtained.

On these temperature-peak load correlations, a regression model is applied to quantify the relation. A linear regression model is applied for cities that are in the cooling regime only, and a segmented model for the cities that have both cooling and heating regimes. The below lefward figure shows the segmented fitting for New York City and the below rightward figure shows the linear fitting for Accra. The coefficients (heating and cooling) and beakpoint cooridinnates (x=threshold temperature; y=baseload load) are extracted and saved for every city at every hour. Note that cities in cooling regime only have a cooling coefficient. This is repeated for scaled values of peak load.

Having derived the overall and scaled maximum cooling coefficients for all the cities, this section consists in visualizing them to define some trends under which cities can be characterized.

Latitude Analysis

Significant Test for Coefficients Deriving a scatterplot of scaled peak cooling coefficient and latitude for every city, a general trend can be noticed:

From the figure we can see that: as cities get away from the Equator, the sensitivity of their peak electricty demand to temperature increases. The boxplot below shows a more clear distribution of per capita scaled cooling coefficient, then we can bring up hypotheses accordingly:

H1. Cooling coefficient in the north is higher than sub-tropics; H2. Cooling coefficient in sub-tropics is higher than tropics; H3. Cooling coefficient in the north is higher than tropics;

We first used ANOVA test to see if the coefficient means of the three groups are equal. Use \(\mu_n\),\(\mu_s\),and \(\mu_t\) to denote the means of the distribution in North, Subtropics and Tropics respectively. Then the null hypothesis in this test will be:

\[ \mu_{n} = \mu_{s} =\mu_{t} \]

The output of the ANOVA test results are as below.

## subtropic-north  -0.0364511 -0.1740011  0.101098876 0.7955699
## tropic-north     -0.1532739 -0.3108572  0.004309366 0.0580275
## tropic-subtropic -0.1168228 -0.2255656 -0.008080027 0.0329006

Since the p-value is 0.0580275, we can reject the null hypothesis at 90% confidence level and conclude that at least one of the distribution has different mean from the others among the three. Then the results of Tukey’s test gave us more insight of the relationships that only between tropic and north groups shows a significant difference in cooling coefficient means.

Based on the results from ANOVA test, we then conducted two-pair comparison to test for H3: cooling coefficient in the north is higher than tropics. The null hypothsis for the test is “Cooling coefficient in the north is lower than tropics”.

\[ H_{0}: \mu_{t} \geq \mu_{n} \]

We first used F test to see if they have same variances. The results are as below. Since the p-value (0.1979) is large enough for us to not reject the null hypothesis, then we can say the two distributions have the same variance. Given the conclusion that the two distributions have same variances, we can conduct equal-variance t test and the results are given. Since the p-value = 0.005125, we can reject the null hypothesis at 99% confidence level and conclude that cooling coefficient in the north is higher than the cooling coefficient in the tropics.

H4. Threshold temperature in the north is lower than sub-tropics; H5. Threshold temperature in sub-tropics is lower than tropics; H6. Threshold temperature in the north is lower than tropics.

P-value of ANOVA test for threshold temperatures is satisfactorily samll – 2.19e-08, which allowed us to reject the null hypothesis at a very high confidence level. Also, from the results of Tukey’s test, we learned that all three two-pair groups have significant intra difference in threshold temperature means.

Based on the results from ANOVA test, we then move on to test the following hypotheses made eariler:

H4. Threshold temperature in the north is lower than sub-tropics; H5. Threshold temperature in sub-tropics is lower than tropics; H6. Threshold temperature in the north is lower than tropics.

Following are the summaries and outputs of F test and t test for the three two-pair comparisons:

To sum up, we successfully proved the 4 hypotheses (H3-H6) in the previous section that 1) cooling coefficient in the north is higher than tropics; 2) threshold temperature in the north is lower than subtropics, and the subtropics is lower than the tropics.

So far, the research managed to test the hypotheses on inter-group coefficient difference and threshold temperature with respect to latitude. Our results showed 1) even though the variances in coefficient donnot differ among the three groups, there is a significant difference in means between north and tropics that cooling coefficient in the north is bigger than the tropics; 2) the variances in threshod temperature only differ for subtropis-tropics group, and all three groups showed significant differences in means in intra-group comparison that “north < subtropis < tropics” is true. Explanation for the observations could be: since cities in the north experience more diverse seasons and have wider range of temperature change throughout the year, people are more sensitive to the hot weather; on the other hand, cities in the tropics have much more stable weather all year round, and the temperature don’t vary much during a day, therefore, people either are more used to the hot temperature and feel no need to use cooling appliances, or the temperature doesn’t vary much enough for the sensitivity to show. Other reasons could also be: cities in the north are richer and more urbanized than those in the tropics. This would be another theory to test in the next stage of our research.

However, the first two hypotheses are not supported by the data, but we don’t rush to deny it since the sample size we have on hand is still limited and there are latitude gap not covered by our sample. We will collect more data in subtropics and more importantly tropics and see if the result would change given sufficient data. Nevertheless, if the difference still doesn’t show, we can still find reasonable explanation that since summer in the subtropics are similar to the tropics, the cooling coefficients are similar between these two groups.

GDP Analysis

In this section we test if the temperature sensitivity of cities is a funciton of GDP.

Using absolute (unscaled) cooling coefficients derived earlier in the study, the city peak electricity demand sensitivity to high temperatures can be related to socio-economic factors (population and GDP per Capita).

Dividing the city-wide absolute cooling coefficients by the corresponding population size (for the year 2008 for consisteny with GDP data that is uniformly available for year 2008 - population size taken from the UN), and derving the GDP/Capita (for the year 2008) for the cities, the following plot can be obtained:

It can be seen from the above graph that cooling coefficients per capita for tropical and sub-tropical cities are about the same range (from 0 to 2.5e-5 MW/DegC*Capita), independently of GDP/Capita ,apart for El Paso. A reason for this may be that El Paso has cooling and heating regime, which makes them more sensitive to high temperatures compared to cities that only have a cooling regime.

Northern cities exhibit a much higher cooling coefficient per capita than tropical and sub-tropica cities, and their amplitudes do not seem to be directly proportional to GDP/Capita of the city. A reason for that may be that above a certain threshold GDP/Capita, cooling is no longer income sensitive and depends on other factors.

Plotting the threshold temperature againt the GDP/Capita, and ignoring Sacramento and Tropical cities the below plot can be obtained:

It can be seen from the above plot that as the GDP/Capita increase, the threshold temperature decreases.
